#DESCRIPTION
#KEYWORDS('maximum,minimum', 'increase,decrease', 'convex')
#  intervals of increase and decrease, convexity
#  of a fraction of two linear functions
#ENDDESCRIPTION

DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
"PG.pl",
"PGbasicmacros.pl",
"PGchoicemacros.pl",
"PGanswermacros.pl",
"PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl"
);

TEXT(&beginproblem);
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 0;

$a1 = random(2,3,1);
$b1 = random(4,9,1);
$c1 = random(3,6,1);
$d1 = random(1,3,1);
## ad-bc always negative
TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
Consider the function \( f(x) = \frac { $a1 x + $b1 } { $c1 x + $d1 } \).
For this function there are two important intervals:
 \( (-\infty, A) \) and \( (A,\infty) \) where
 the function is not defined at \( A \).
 $BR
Find \( A \) \{ans_rule(10) \}
EOT
$ans = -$d1/$c1;
&ANS(std_num_cmp($ans));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
For each of the following intervals, tell whether \( f(x) \)
is increasing (type in INC) or decreasing (type in DEC).
$BR
 \( (-\infty, A) \): \{ans_rule(10) \}
EOT
$ans = "DEC";
&ANS(std_num_str_cmp($ans,['INC','DEC']));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
\( (A,\infty) \) \{ans_rule(10) \}
EOT
$ans = "DEC";
&ANS(std_num_str_cmp($ans,['INC','DEC']));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
Note that this function has no inflection points, but we can still consider its concavity.
For each of the following intervals, tell whether \( f(x) \)
is concave up (type in CU) or concave down (type in CD).
$BR
 \( (-\infty, A) \): \{ans_rule(10) \}
EOT
$ans = "CD";
&ANS(std_num_str_cmp($ans,['CU','CD']));
TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
\( (A,\infty) \) \{ans_rule(10) \}
EOT
$ans = "CU";
&ANS(std_num_str_cmp($ans,['CU','CD']));
ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.
